  "prompt": "What are proportional taxes?",
  "response": "Proportional taxes, also known as flat taxes, are taxes that impose the same tax rate on all taxpayers regardless of their income level. In other words, everyone pays the same percentage of their income in taxes, regardless of whether they earn a little or a lot.\n\nKey characteristics of proportional taxes include:\n\n1. Consistent tax rate: The tax rate remains constant across all income levels.\n\n2. Equal percentage: Everyone pays the same percentage of their income in taxes.\n\n3. No progressive or regressive elements: Unlike progressive taxes (which increase rates for higher incomes) or regressive taxes (which decrease rates for higher incomes), proportional taxes maintain a steady rate.\n\nExample:\nIf a proportional income tax rate is 10%, then:\n- Someone earning $20,000 would pay $2,000 in taxes\n- Someone earning $100,000 would pay $10,000 in taxes\n\nProportional taxes are relatively rare in practice, with sales taxes being a common example. Some argue they are simple and fair, while others contend they can be less equitable because they may disproportionately burden lower-income individuals.",
